    {
      "unresolved": true,
      "key": {
        "uuid": "3a58e02a_03e0b3a9",
        "filename": "cv/internal/lease/lease.go",
        "patchSetId": 7
      },
      "lineNbr": 210,
      "author": {
        "id": 1114919
      },
      "writtenOn": "2021-01-16T09:22:03Z",
      "side": 1,
      "message": "Strictly speaking, we should round it towards the future. In prod, it doesn\u0027t matter, since clocks aren\u0027t 1us synchronized anyways. But it may matter in tests if fake time has ns component.\ne.g. TestRecentTimeUTC which has 7ns would lead to:\n  tryApply( Application{  now + minute } ) \u003d\u003e Lease{ now + minute - 7s}",
      "revId": "838b2b48686314aaf53bd906cb79641b31a01774",
      "serverId": "3ce6091f-6c88-37e8-8c75-72f92ae8dfba"
    },
    {
      "unresolved": true,
      "key": {
        "uuid": "d5878864_b8351fb9",
        "filename": "cv/internal/lease/lease.go",
        "patchSetId": 7
      },
      "lineNbr": 210,
      "author": {
        "id": 1381059
      },
      "writtenOn": "2021-01-16T20:21:00Z",
      "side": 1,
      "message": "\u003e Strictly speaking, we should round it towards the future. \n\nMay I ask why? I feel like truncating to the precision which a system can support is generally what people do instead of rounding up.\n\nSpeaking of which, I think usually the requested duration will be O(ms) for potentially long-running operation like calling Gerrit. Maybe we should just truncate the app.ExpireTime, lease.ExpireTime and `duration` in Extend method to millisecond precision and document such behavior so that we don\u0027t need to couple with datastore here. WDYT?",
